# tools.lock — pinned absolute paths for hook execution
#
# Purpose
#   Hooks resolve tools via this file instead of $PATH lookups so that PATH
#   manipulation (alias, shadowed binary, dotfile injection) cannot redirect
#   a hook's tool invocation to an attacker-controlled binary.
#
# Format
#   TAB-separated, one tool per line:
#     name<TAB>absolute_path
#   Lines starting with '#' are comments. Blank lines are ignored.
#
# Lifecycle
#   - This file (tools.lock.example) is the COMMITTED contract: the set of
#     tools the hooks declare a dependency on, with reasonable Linux defaults.
#   - The active file is scripts/hooks/lib/tools.lock (gitignored). Generate
#     it with:  scripts/hooks/lib/tools-init.sh
#   - Treat upgrades as security events: re-run tools-init.sh deliberately
#     after package updates and review the diff before continuing.
#
# Strict mode
#   Set ARCHETYPE_HOOK_TOOLS_STRICT=1 to make unpinned tools a hard error.
#   Default is fail-soft: hook_resolve_tool falls back to `command -v`.
git	/usr/bin/git
jq	/usr/bin/jq
python3	/usr/bin/python3
gh	/usr/bin/gh
bash	/usr/bin/bash
sha256sum	/usr/bin/sha256sum
find	/usr/bin/find
sed	/usr/bin/sed
tr	/usr/bin/tr
wc	/usr/bin/wc
date	/usr/bin/date
stat	/usr/bin/stat
